Introduction¶

The dataset originally contained information on 113,937 personal loans given by Prosper to borrowers with at least a credit score of 600. After cleaning out an out of range Prosper score, 11.0, the dataset for the investigation now contains 112481 borrowers information. On each loan, there are 81 variables including the loan original amount, borrower rate, stated monthly income, monthly loan payment, employment status, Prosper score, current loan status, and many others. Prosper used a proprietary rating system that considered data points like credit history and debt-to-income ratio to determine the Prosper score of a borrower, which investors relied on to decide whether to fund the loan or not. Most loans were funded within three days, and potential borrowers whose applications were not at least 70% funded expired within 14 days.

# The LoanOriginalAmount is a quantitative variable, and its distribution can appropriately be understood by a histrogram

fig = plt.figure(figsize = [20, 6])

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
bins = np.arange(0, df_clean['LoanOriginalAmount'].max()+100, 1500);
plt.hist(data = df_clean, x = 'LoanOriginalAmount', bins = bins);
plt.xlabel('Loan Original Amount, ($)')
plt.ylabel('count')


plt.subplot(1,2,2)
bins1 = 10**np.arange(3, 4.5+0.01, 0.04);

# Generate the x-ticks you want to apply
ticks = [1000, 1800, 3000, 4500, 6000, 9000, 12000, 18000, 24000, 32000]

# Convert ticks into string values, to be displaye dlong the x-axis
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]

plt.hist(data = df_clean, x = 'LoanOriginalAmount', bins = bins1);

plt.xlabel('Logarithmic Loan Original Amount, ($)')
plt.ylabel('count')

plt.xscale('log');

# Apply x-ticks
plt.xticks(ticks, labels);

Observation:¶

The visualization reveals that the loan original amount is unimodal and is skewed to the right with loan amounts less than 10000 dollars being given to the most of borrowers. With the exception of the loan amounts between the 15000 and 16000 bin having a count of about 14000 borrowers, all other amounts beyond 11000 have count of borrowers less than 5000.

User-defined function for plotting bar charts

In [18]:
def anycountplot(df, xVar, ordertype):
    
    figure = plt.figure(figsize = [12, 8])
    
    ax = sb.countplot(data = df, x = xVar, order = ordertype, color = base_color);
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)

    ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0])
    plt.show()

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Majority of the borrowers who were given loans for scoring 4.0 on the Prosper score scale had current loans.

The employment status however interacted differently with Prosper score and the loan original amount, as borrowers of the employment status Self-employed and Employed were more likely to receive a higher Prosper score and a corresponding higher loan original amount compared to the borrowers who classified under the other types of employment status. The borrowers of the levels Self-employed and Employed were also respectively more than those of the other levels of employment status.

Irrespective of the loan original amount, most of the borrowers were charged an APR between 0.1 and 0.4. Despite this range for the borrower APR, any increase in the loan original amount witnessed a corresponding increase in the monthly loan payment.

Completed, DefaultedLoanStatus and ChargedOff were the loan status that interacted with the borrower state across the range of the loan original amount. Different levels of the loan status distributed differently across the states. While some of the distributions were unimodal, others were multimodal. The median loan original amount was different for all the loan status levels of all the borrower states.

¶

Conclusions¶

Data exploration analysis (EDA) conclusions¶

Various features of a loan interacted differently with the loan original amount, the feature of interest.

The data exploration analysis revealed that loan approvals and the loan original amount given to borrowers were highly influenced by the Prosper score and the state of the borrower. Higher Prosper score corresponded to higher loan amounts. Borrowers from certain states including CA, GA, II, FL, NY and TX were more likely to receive large loan amounts. Comparatively, these borrowers were also the most of Prosper loan customers.

Higher loan original amounts implied that borrowers were also going to make higer monthly loan payments towards paying off their loans and vice versa. Borrower APR are normally higher for recipients of higher loan amounts. The ownership of a home didn't impact the number of borrowers and the loan amount granted by Prosper loan to applicants.

Reflection on the steps taken in carrying out the EDA¶

In performing the data exploration analysis, the initial focus was on understanding how each of the features necessary to investigate the loan original amount were individually distributed. Bar charts and histograms were plotted to study these individual distributions of the features. Numerical data were plotted using histograms, while bar plots were created for categorical data type features which were either nominal or ordinal. For nominal categorical features, horizontal bar plots were created and it was preferred to enable all the levels of the feature to be captured visibly in the plot. Otherwise, the vertical bar plots were used. The distribution of the quantitative features that were investigated were generally right-skewed, and log-transformation was employed to build the normal distributions of the features to gain a better.

Following the univariate exploration, interest was now in understanding how the other features related with either the loan original amount or among themselves. Depending on the combination of features, bivariate analysis plot types and techniques including box plots, violin plots, scatter plots and faceting were used.

Multivariate analysis was conducted to investigate how a combination of the other features interacted with and influenced the loan original amount. Faceting involving box plot, scatter plot and violin plot sufficed to achieve the objective of building multivariate plots.
